Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - President Cyril Ramaphosa says the COVID-19 pandemic has impacted negatively on workers. Ramaphosa delivered two addresses on Workers' Day, one as leader of South Africa and another in his capacity as President of the African National Congress (ANC). During these addresses, he acknowledged the economic havoc caused by the COVID-19 across the globe. Ramaphosa also says the challenges that the country faced before democracy have become worse. South Africa entered into level four lockdown on Workers' Day and some restrictions have been relaxed. READ: Revised level four lockdown regulations Almost 1.5-million people are set to return to work, while public transport can be utilised at all times of the day but with restrictions. However, schools remain closed for at least until next month. READ: SA lockdown: Schools to remain closed in May The number of COVID-19 cases in South Africa increased to 5,647 with the death toll at 103.